1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,849
This laboratory supplies you with every possible example of human action.

2
00:00:05,040 --> 00:00:11,730
And there is no limit to what you can learn once you see yourself as a scientist in your own lab.

3
00:00:12,079 --> 00:00:14,450
What's more, there is nothing to buy.

4
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:16,210
There is no rent to pay.

5
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:18,450
There are no fees of any kind.

6
00:00:18,640 --> 00:00:22,849
You can use this laboratory as much as you like for free.

7
00:00:23,440 --> 00:00:31,089
As director of your own laboratory, you will want to do what every scientist does, observe and experiment.

8
00:00:31,760 --> 00:00:38,530
Isn't it surprising to you that most people understand so little about why people act as they do,

9
00:00:38,640 --> 00:00:41,889
even though they are surrounded by people all their lives?

10
00:00:42,320 --> 00:00:44,930
Most people are not trained observers.

11
00:00:45,280 --> 00:00:50,530
One important purpose of this book is to help you train yourself to observe,

12
00:00:50,640 --> 00:00:53,649
to develop deep insight into human action.

13
00:00:53,920 --> 00:01:00,770
You'll want to ask yourself questions like, Why is John so successful and Tom just getting by?

14
00:01:01,040 --> 00:01:06,210
Why do some people have many friends and other people have only few friends?

15
00:01:06,400 --> 00:01:13,730
Why will people gladly accept what one person tells them but ignore another person who tells them the same thing?

16
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:21,010
Once trained, you will learn valuable lessons just through the very simple process of observing.

17
00:01:21,520 --> 00:01:26,369
Here are two special suggestions to help you make yourself a trained observer.

18
00:01:26,720 --> 00:01:32,930
Select for special study the most successful and the most unsuccessful person you know.

19
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:40,609
Then, as the book unfolds, observe how closely your successful friend adheres to these success principles.

20
00:01:40,880 --> 00:01:50,290
Notice also how studying the two extremes will help you see the unmistakable wisdom of following the truths outlined in this book.

21
00:01:50,960 --> 00:01:57,889
Each contact you make with another person gives you a chance to see success development principles at work.

22
00:01:58,079 --> 00:02:01,810
Your objective is to make successful action habitual.

23
00:02:01,920 --> 00:02:07,649
The more we practice, the sooner it becomes second nature to act in the desired way.

24
00:02:08,240 --> 00:02:11,810
Most of us have friends who grow things for a hobby.

25
00:02:11,920 --> 00:02:17,010
And we've all heard them say something like, it's exciting to watch those plants grow.

26
00:02:17,120 --> 00:02:20,290
Just look how they respond to plant food and water.

27
00:02:20,480 --> 00:02:24,050
See how much bigger they are today than they were last week.

28
00:02:24,720 --> 00:02:31,010
To be sure, it is thrilling to watch what can happen when men cooperate carefully with nature.

29
00:02:31,280 --> 00:02:39,810
But it is not one-tenth as fascinating as watching yourself respond to your own carefully administered thought-management program.

30
00:02:40,079 --> 00:02:47,889
It's fun to feel yourself growing more confident, more effective, more successful, day by day, month by month.

31
00:02:48,320 --> 00:02:56,930
Nothing, absolutely nothing, in this life gives you more satisfaction than knowing you're on the road to success and achievement.

32
00:02:57,120 --> 00:03:01,970
And nothing stands as a bigger challenge than making the most of yourself.

